	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pliny, <I>Natural History</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">VII</SPAN>.29.108</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note28" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Alexandri*/1.html#ref28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">28</A>
That is, of occupying himself with Peripatetic (Aristotelian) philosophy.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note29" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Alexandri*/1.html#ref29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">29</A>
It is interesting to note that dialogues bearing the names of all these pupils have been handed down to us under the name of Plato, although some of them are thought to be spurious.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note30" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Alexandri*/1.html#ref30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30</A>
Wyttenbach in sadness doubts whether these ethnological remarks are the fruit of any research on the part of Plutarch. But they probably derive from a hazy recollection of such passages as
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/1D*.html#216
	"TARGET="Herodotus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Herodotus,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Herodotus, <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.216
	</A>
(of the Massagetae). Note, however, that Strabo supports Plutarch on this custom of the Persians
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/15C*.html#3.20
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<SPAN CLASS="small">XV</SPAN>.3.20)</A>, which is easily explained by the


<A ID="p393x"></A><SPAN CLASS="pagenum">(p393)</SPAN>fact that the young king inherited his father's harem as well as his father's stable, and that the father's younger wives furnished the beginning of the son's harem. <I>Cf.</I> also Sophocles, <I>Trachiniae</I>, 1221‑1251. For other pleasant customs of the Hyrcanians <I>cf.</I> <I>Moralia</I>, 499<SPAN CLASS="small">D</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Alexandri*/1.html#ref31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diogenes_Laertius/Lives_of_the_Eminent_Philosophers/4/Clitomachus*.html#67
	"TARGET="Diogenes_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Diogenes Laertius, <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.67</A>; Athenaeus, 402<SPAN CLASS="small">C</SPAN><!--</A>ATHENAEUS402-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Alexandri*/1.html#ref32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A>
Diogenes, from Seleucia in Mesopotamia (<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/16A*.html#1.16
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
